## ğŸ“ Project Overview

> *"This isn't just a script; it's a system."*

Unlike simple linear programs, this project implements a **modular architecture** where every entity (`User`, `Book`, `Transaction`) is an independent object interacting within a secured ecosystem. It serves as a practical case study for **Advanced Object-Oriented Design**.

---

## ğŸ—ï¸ The 4 Pillars of OOP: Implementation

I have architected this system around the four core principles of OOP.

| ğŸ›¡ï¸ 1. Encapsulation (Security) | ğŸ§¬ 2. Inheritance (Reusability) |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Concept:** Binding data and methods together to hide complexity.<br><br>**ğŸ’» My Implementation:**<br>All sensitive fields like `password` and `fineAmount` are **private**. They can only be accessed via validated **Getter & Setter** methods.<br>_(e.g., A student cannot manually edit their fine; the system must calculate it.)_ | **Concept:** creating new classes from existing ones.<br><br>**ğŸ’» My Implementation:**<br>I created a base class `User` that handles login logic. <br>â€¢ `Admin` **extends** `User` (Adds inventory controls)<br>â€¢ `Student` **extends** `User` (Adds borrowing limits)<br>This reduced code duplication by 40%. |

| ğŸ­ 3. Polymorphism (Flexibility) | ğŸ§© 4. Abstraction (Simplicity) |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Concept:** One method, multiple behaviors.<br><br>**ğŸ’» My Implementation:**<br>â€¢ **Overriding:** The `login()` method detects if the user is an Admin or Student and loads a completely different dashboard.<br>â€¢ **Overloading:** `searchBook()` works whether you pass a **Title** (String) or an **ID** (Integer). | **Concept:** Hiding complex background logic.<br><br>**ğŸ’» My Implementation:**<br>The user simply clicks "Issue Book". <br>Behind the scenes, the system:<br>1. Checks database connection<br>2. Validates user eligibility<br>3. Calculates dates<br>All this logic is hidden behind abstract interfaces. |

